  <h2 id="why-email-backup-matters">Why Email Backup Matters</h2>
  <p>
    Most people assume their emails are safe because they live in the cloud. In reality, there are several scenarios where you could lose access to your entire email history overnight.
  </p>

  <h3>Data Loss and Accidental Deletion</h3>
  <p>
    It takes a single misclick to permanently delete a folder of important emails. Many providers move deleted messages to trash, but trash folders are automatically purged after 30 days. If you do not notice the deletion within that window, the messages are gone. Bulk operations, filter rules that auto-delete, and sync errors between devices are all common causes of accidental data loss.
  </p>

  <h3>Account Compromise</h3>
  <p>
    If an attacker gains access to your email account, they can delete all your messages, change your password, and lock you out permanently. Even after recovering your account, there is no guarantee that deleted messages can be restored. High-profile account takeovers happen regularly, and email accounts are prime targets because they are the gateway to password resets for every other service you use.
  </p>

  <h3>Provider Shutdown and Migration</h3>
  <p>
    Email services do not last forever. Smaller providers shut down, free tiers get discontinued, and corporate email systems get migrated to new platforms. When Google announced changes to its unlimited storage offerings, organizations scrambled to export years of email data on short notice. Having regular backups means you are never caught off guard by a provider change.
  </p>

