  <h2 id="email-backup-methods">Email Backup Methods</h2>
  <p>
    There are several approaches to backing up your email, each with different trade-offs in terms of portability, ease of use, and completeness.
  </p>

  <h3>Export as EML Files</h3>
  <p>
    EML (Electronic Mail) is an open standard format that stores individual email messages as plain text files following the RFC 822 specification. Each EML file contains the complete message: headers, body text, HTML content, and all attachments encoded inline. Because EML is an open standard, these files can be opened by virtually any email client, including Thunderbird, Apple Mail, Windows Mail, and browser-based viewers like <a href="/tools/eml/">OpenedFile's EML Viewer</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    EML is the best format for portable, long-term email backups. Files are self-contained, human-readable, and do not depend on any proprietary software. The one-file-per-message structure also makes it easy to organize, search, and selectively restore specific emails.
  </p>

  <h3>PST Export from Outlook</h3>
  <p>
    Microsoft Outlook uses the PST (Personal Storage Table) format to store emails, contacts, calendar entries, and other mailbox data in a single file. PST is a convenient backup option for Outlook users because it preserves folder structure, categories, and flags. However, PST is a proprietary Microsoft format. Opening PST files requires Outlook or specialized third-party tools, which makes it a poor choice for long-term archival if you might switch platforms in the future.
  </p>

  <h3>IMAP Backup Tools</h3>
  <p>
    IMAP backup tools connect to your email server using the IMAP protocol and download all messages to your local machine. Tools like <strong>imapbackup</strong>, <strong>OfflineIMAP</strong>, <strong>mbsync</strong>, and <strong>Thunderbird</strong> (acting as a local client) can mirror your entire mailbox to local storage. This approach works with any IMAP-compatible email service, including Gmail, Outlook.com, Yahoo Mail, and corporate Exchange servers. Many of these tools can export directly to EML or Maildir format for maximum portability.
  </p>

  <h2 id="cloud-vs-local-storage">Cloud vs. Local Storage</h2>
  <p>
    Once you have exported your emails, you need to decide where to store the backup. Both cloud storage and local storage have advantages and disadvantages.
  </p>

  <h3>Cloud Storage</h3>
  <p>
    Storing email backups in cloud services such as Google Drive, Dropbox, OneDrive, or Amazon S3 provides geographic redundancy, meaning your data survives even if your home is damaged by a fire or flood. Cloud backups are also accessible from any device with internet access, which is convenient when you need to find an old email quickly.
  </p>
  <p>
    The downsides of cloud storage include ongoing subscription costs, dependence on yet another online service, and potential privacy concerns. You are essentially trusting another company with your sensitive email data. If the cloud provider suffers a breach, your email backups could be exposed.
  </p>

  <h3>Local Storage</h3>
  <p>
    Storing backups on external hard drives, USB drives, or NAS (Network Attached Storage) devices gives you full physical control over your data. There are no monthly fees, no privacy risks from third parties, and no dependency on internet connectivity. For sensitive personal or business emails, local storage offers the strongest privacy guarantees.
  </p>
  <p>
    The risks of local-only storage include hardware failure, theft, and damage from fire or flooding. A single external hard drive is not a reliable backup because all storage devices eventually fail. The solution is redundancy: keep copies on at least two separate physical devices, ideally stored in different locations.
  </p>

