  <p>
    Pay special attention to these common issues when verifying backups:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Missing attachments</strong> — Some export methods strip attachments or fail to include large files. Verify that attachments are present and downloadable.</li>
    <li><strong>Encoding errors</strong> — Emails with non-ASCII characters (international languages, special symbols) may display incorrectly if the export tool handled character encoding poorly.</li>
    <li><strong>Zero-byte files</strong> — Occasionally, export processes create empty EML files. Check that file sizes are reasonable; a typical email with no attachments is 2 to 50 KB.</li>
    <li><strong>Truncated messages</strong> — Very long emails or emails with large inline content may be truncated during export. Compare the exported file against the original message in your email client.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="backup-schedule-recommendations">Backup Schedule Recommendations</h2>
  <p>
    How often you back up your email depends on how much email you receive and how critical it is. Here are general guidelines for different use cases:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Personal email (light use)</strong> — A quarterly backup is usually sufficient. Set a calendar reminder to export new emails every three months.</li>
    <li><strong>Personal email (heavy use)</strong> — Monthly backups are recommended if you receive important correspondence regularly, such as financial statements, medical records, or legal documents.</li>
    <li><strong>Business email</strong> — Weekly or bi-weekly backups are appropriate for professional accounts. Many businesses have compliance requirements that mandate email retention for specific periods.</li>
    <li><strong>Critical or regulated industries</strong> — Daily automated backups using IMAP backup tools are recommended for industries with strict compliance requirements, such as healthcare (HIPAA), finance (SOX), or legal (litigation hold requirements).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Regardless of your schedule, always perform an immediate backup before any major account change, such as switching email providers, migrating to a new domain, or changing your organization's email platform.
  </p>

  <h2 id="long-term-archival-best-practices">Long-Term Archival Best Practices</h2>
  <p>
    If you want your email backups to remain accessible for years or even decades, follow these archival best practices:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use open formats</strong> — Store emails as EML files rather than proprietary formats like PST or MSG. EML is based on open RFC standards and can be read by any compliant software, regardless of which companies exist in the future.</li>
    <li><strong>Organize by date and folder</strong> — Create a clear directory structure for your backups, such as <code>email-backup/2026/inbox/</code> or <code>email-backup/2026/work-projects/</code>. This makes it easy to locate specific emails without specialized search tools.</li>
    <li><strong>Include metadata</strong> — Save a text file alongside each backup set that documents when the export was performed, which account it came from, how many messages were exported, and which tool was used. This metadata is invaluable when revisiting backups years later.</li>
    <li><strong>Follow the 3-2-1 rule</strong> — Keep at least <strong>3 copies</strong> of your backup, on <strong>2 different types of storage media</strong>, with <strong>1 copy stored offsite</strong>. For example: one copy on your computer's hard drive, one on an external SSD, and one encrypted copy in the cloud.</li>
    <li><strong>Test periodically</strong> — Every six months, open a few EML files from your archive to confirm they are still readable. Storage media degrades over time, and catching corruption early gives you a chance to restore from a redundant copy.</li>
    <li><strong>Refresh storage media</strong> — Hard drives and SSDs have limited lifespans. Every three to five years, copy your backups to new storage devices. Optical media such as Blu-ray can last longer, but it should still be verified periodically.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Email is one of the most important digital records most people possess. A consistent backup routine using portable formats like EML, combined with redundant storage and periodic verification, ensures that your correspondence remains safe and accessible no matter what happens to your email provider or devices.
  </p>

